<DOC><DOCNO> AP890427-0082 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0844EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh-Tornadoes 1stLd-Writethru a0522 04-27 0359</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Bangladesh-Tornadoes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0522,0364</SECOND><HEAD>Tornado Kills 176, Rains Come After 2-Month Drought</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with death toll at 176. Pickup8th graf, `Another tornado...'</HEAD><BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   After people prayed for rain to relievea drought, two tornadoes and heavy rains battered rural Bangladesh,killing at least 176 people and injuring hundreds, the state newsagency said today.   The agency, Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha, did not cite a sourcefor the death toll but gave the figure in a story that saidPresident Hussain Muhammad Ershad had ordered relief and rescueoperations for victims of a tornado Wednesday night in theManikganj area.   An independent news agency, United News of Bangladesh, put thedeath toll at 42, citing reports from its correspondent inManikganj, 25 miles northwest of Dhaka. The tornado, with winds of100 mph, hailstones, and drenching showers came hours after Ershadordered nationwide prayers for rain.   In Dhaka alone, more than 75,000 people joined Ershad in aprayer service.   Two months of drought had threatened to destroy more than halfthe rice crop in this poverty-stricken nation. Agricultureofficials said more rain would be needed in the coming week to savethe crops.   The government news agency said 22 bodies were found in therubble of fallen mud and straw houses. The news agency did not givedetails.   At least 200 of the injured were hospitalized, thegovernment-owned newspaper Dainik Bangla said. It said scores ofpeople were missing after their boats capsized on the Padma River,25 miles northwest of Dhaka.   Another tornado hit the Narsingdi district, 25 miles east of thecapital, killing five people and injuring 500, the English-languageNew Nation said. The independent daily said about 200,000 peoplewere affected by the tornadoes.   The newspapers said thousands of mud-and-straw houses were sweptaway. The tornadoes snapped communications links between Dhaka andmuch of the country.   Bangladesh, one of the world's poorest countries with a percapita annual income of $160, alternates between flood and drought.Agriculture is the main occupation of the majority of the country's110 million people.</TEXT></DOC>